# IPL Query Engine — Natural Language to SQL

> Ask any IPL question in plain English. AI writes the SQL. You get the answer.

**"Who hit the most sixes in IPL history?"** → SQL generated → Answer in under 2 seconds.

Live demo powered by **Groq + LLaMA 3** on **278,205 balls** of real IPL data (2008–2025).

---

##  What This Project Does

A **Text-to-SQL** application where anyone — cricket fan or data analyst — can ask questions in natural language and get accurate, data-backed answers without writing a single line of SQL.

The output isn't just a boring table. Results render as **smart dashboards**:
- 🏏 **Player queries** → Hero card with Wikipedia photo + ranked player cards
- 🏆 **Team queries** → Team cards with official IPL logos
- 📊 **Season queries** → Animated bar charts
- 📋 **General stats** → Gold leaderboard with progress bars

---

##  Features

- Plain English → SQL → Beautiful dashboard in seconds
- Wikipedia photos auto-fetched for top-ranked players
- Official IPL team logos for all 13 franchises
- Smart result type detection (player cards / team cards / chart / leaderboard)
- Schema-aware LLM prompting for high SQL accuracy
- Groq cloud LLM (free, sub-second) with local Ollama fallback
- Handles historical team name aliases (Delhi Daredevils → Delhi Capitals)
- Query history tracking with latency display
- IPL-themed dark UI — stadium night aesthetic

---

## Project Structure

```
ipl-sql-generator/
│
├── data/                         # Raw CSV files (IPL dataset 2008–2025)
│   ├── teams_data.csv
│   ├── team_aliases.csv
│   ├── players-data-updated.csv
│   ├── ipl_matches_data.csv
│   └── ball_by_ball_data.csv
│
├── venv/                         # Python virtual environment (not pushed to GitHub)
├── .env                          # API keys — never pushed to GitHub
├── .gitignore
│
├── database.py                   # Builds ipl.db from CSVs + schema for LLM
├── llm.py                        # LLM wrapper — Groq (primary) + Ollama (fallback)
├── query_runner.py               # Safely executes SQL against ipl.db
├── api.py                        # FastAPI backend — single /query endpoint
├── index.html                    # Full frontend UI — one file, no framework
│
├── requirements.txt
└── README.md
```

> **Note:** `ipl.db`, `venv/`, `data/` and `.env` are excluded from GitHub (see `.gitignore`).  
> Download the dataset from [Kaggle](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/maratheabhishek/ipl-dataset-2008-to-2025) and run `python database.py` to build the DB locally.

---

##  Database

| Table | Rows | Description |
|-------|------|-------------|
| `teams` | 16 | IPL franchises |
| `team_aliases` | 46 | Historical name mappings |
| `players` | 772 | Player profiles — batting/bowling style, role |
| `matches` | 1,169 | Match-level data — venue, toss, winner, margin |
| `deliveries` | 278,205 | Ball-by-ball — every run, wicket, extra ever bowled |

The `deliveries` table is the heart of the project — it enables granular queries like powerplay economy rates, player vs player matchups, death-over analysis, and boundary percentages.

---

## How It Works

```
User types question in English
           ↓
      api.py receives it
           ↓
   llm.py builds a prompt
   (question + full DB schema)
           ↓
   Groq runs LLaMA 3 (free)
   returns raw SQL query
           ↓
  query_runner.py executes SQL
  on ipl.db (SQLite)
           ↓
  index.html renders result
  as player cards / team cards
  / chart / leaderboard
```

---

## Tech Stack

| Layer | Technology |
|-------|-----------|
| **LLM** | LLaMA 3 via Groq API (free, ~0.8s latency) |
| **LLM Fallback** | Ollama (local, offline) |
| **Backend** | Python, FastAPI, Uvicorn |
| **Database** | SQLite (via Pandas + sqlite3) |
| **Frontend** | Pure HTML / CSS / JavaScript (no framework) |
| **Photos** | Wikipedia REST API (free, no key) |
| **Team Logos** | Wikipedia SVG files |
| **Data Processing** | Pandas |

---

## Getting Started

### 1. Clone the repo
```bash
git clone https://github.com/yourusername/ipl-sql-generator.git
cd ipl-sql-generator
```

### 2. Download the dataset
Download from [Kaggle](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/maratheabhishek/ipl-dataset-2008-to-2025) and place all 5 CSVs in the `data/` folder.

### 3. Set up virtual environment
```bash
python -m venv venv
venv\Scripts\activate        # Windows
source venv/bin/activate     # Mac/Linux
```

### 4. Install dependencies
```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

### 5. Add your free Groq API key
Get a free key at [console.groq.com](https://console.groq.com) — takes 2 minutes, no credit card.
```
# .env
GROQ_API_KEY=gsk_your_key_here
```

### 6. Build the database
```bash
python database.py
```

### 7. Run the server
```bash
python -m uvicorn api:app --reload
```

### 8. Open in browser
```
http://localhost:8000
```

